    <a title="Catherine" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2059285-catherine"><img alt="Catherine" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1235336603p2/2059285.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/254747334?book_show_action=true">Jan 02, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Catherine" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Catherine" href="/user/show/2059285-catherine">Catherine</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780552151290" href="/book/show/133866.Jihad_vs_McWorld">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2059285-catherine?shelf=bookcrossing">bookcrossing</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer254747334" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10215550970075790713">Surprisingly, given the title, this book is over ten years old although this British edition has a foreword post - but not much post - 9/11. The Jihad of which it speaks is more to do with the impulse towards fragmentation of states, petty nationalism and tribalism than specifically religious movements, while its McWorld is the forces of globalisation - almost entirely commercial. The key point seems to be that the relationship between the two is one of mutual dependence as much as, or probably </span>
  <span id="freeText10215550970075790713" style="display:none">Surprisingly, given the title, this book is over ten years old although this British edition has a foreword post - but not much post - 9/11. The Jihad of which it speaks is more to do with the impulse towards fragmentation of states, petty nationalism and tribalism than specifically religious movements, while its McWorld is the forces of globalisation - almost entirely commercial. The key point seems to be that the relationship between the two is one of mutual dependence as much as, or probably more than, the commonly accepted mutual destruction. While there are some amusing nuggets - especially reading it during the News of the World phone hacking scandal - the tone is serious. I thought in aiming to present arguments for his thesis thoroughly Barber ended up coming across as over-earnest and the book too long. A decently edited edition might have more impact.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10215550970075790713" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
