    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1183605557" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1183605557" />
    <a title="Gerald" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1992552-gerald"><img alt="Gerald" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1416066149p2/1992552.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1183605557?book_show_action=true">Jan 28, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gerald" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gerald" href="/user/show/1992552-gerald">Gerald</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1183605557" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17842827798011119298">At the time I read this book (soon after it was published in 1995) Barber&apos;s concepts were new to me, His main premise in the book is that the opposing forces of tribalism and consumerism are creating a tension in the world that leads to interesting and often volatile consequences. The last twenty years have seen this concept play out countless times and although I haven&apos;t read the book in this century, I feel that it will remain insightful for those looking to gain greater understanding of our c</span>
  <span id="freeText17842827798011119298" style="display:none">At the time I read this book (soon after it was published in 1995) Barber's concepts were new to me, His main premise in the book is that the opposing forces of tribalism and consumerism are creating a tension in the world that leads to interesting and often volatile consequences. The last twenty years have seen this concept play out countless times and although I haven't read the book in this century, I feel that it will remain insightful for those looking to gain greater understanding of our complex and often baffling world.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17842827798011119298" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

