<div id="review_2518647626" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2518647626" />
    <a title="Choong Chiat" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5267099-choong-chiat"><img alt="Choong Chiat" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1362304008p2/5267099.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2518647626?book_show_action=true">Nov 11, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Choong Chiat" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Choong Chiat" href="/user/show/5267099-choong-chiat">Choong Chiat</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2518647626" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5797269597804079670">This book argues that unrestrained economic globalisation/consumerism (i.e. McWorld) is in a struggle with tribalism/identity politics (i.e. Jihad) and that these two opposing forces and the struggle between them is undermining democracy. He proposes having an active (global) civil society as the first step in overcoming the effects of these two forces and the struggle between them.<br/><br/>Although first written more than two decades ago and meandering at times, this book does not feel outdated (not sur</span>
  <span id="freeText5797269597804079670" style="display:none">This book argues that unrestrained economic globalisation/consumerism (i.e. McWorld) is in a struggle with tribalism/identity politics (i.e. Jihad) and that these two opposing forces and the struggle between them is undermining democracy. He proposes having an active (global) civil society as the first step in overcoming the effects of these two forces and the struggle between them.<br /><br />Although first written more than two decades ago and meandering at times, this book does not feel outdated (not sure whether this is a good thing, given the book's grim description of the state of affairs back in the mid 1990s). It still manages to raise thought-provoking points relevant to our current times approaching the third decade of the 21st century; a few of the points (e.g. the dangers of leaving internet technology entirely in the hands of profit-driven corporations) in fact seem somewhat prescient.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5797269597804079670" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


